        "number": "1",
        "title": "\"Will This Actually Work With My Skin — Or Just Sit On Top Of It?\"",
        "body_text": "<p>This is the question that separates women who love their foundation from women who've given up on it entirely. Most foundations are designed to create a layer on top of your skin. A coating. A mask. And for women over 40, whose skin texture, moisture levels, and elasticity have fundamentally changed, that approach is a recipe for disappointment.</p><p>A foundation that sits on the surface will settle into fine lines within hours. It will slide off areas where your skin produces less oil. It will cling to dry patches and skip over the spots that actually need coverage. You'll spend the day checking mirrors and wondering why it looked fine at 7am and terrible by noon.</p><p>The right foundation bonds with your skin rather than sitting on it. It uses micro-pigment technology that flexes with your facial movements instead of cracking. It works with your skin's natural moisture rather than fighting it. Before you buy anything, ask the brand: does this formula work differently on mature skin, or is it just the same formula with different marketing?</p>",
        "link_text": "",
        "link_type": "anchor",
        "link_anchor": "",
        "link_url": "",
        "image_asset": "lp-questions-foundation-reason-1.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
    },
    "bl_reason_item_78kciy": {
      "type": "bl-reason-item",
      "name": "BL - Reason Item",
      "settings": {
        "section_id": "",
        "bg_color": "#faf9f7",
        "number": "2",
        "title": "\"What Happens To This Foundation After 4 Hours?\"",
        "body_text": "<p>Every foundation looks acceptable at the moment of application. The real test is what happens at hour four, hour six, hour ten. And this is where the vast majority of foundations designed for younger skin completely fall apart on women over 40.</p><p>Here's what typically happens: the formula oxidises, shifting to a darker or more orange shade as it reacts with your skin's pH. The pigments migrate into fine lines, making them appear deeper. Any areas of dryness — which become more common with age — start to show through as the formula loses adhesion. By late afternoon, you're not wearing the foundation you applied that morning. You're wearing a degraded version of it.</p><p>A foundation worth buying should look better at 6pm than it did at 8am. That's not a fantasy — it's what happens when the formula contains hydrating ingredients that actually improve your skin throughout the day. Hyaluronic acid draws moisture in. Vitamin E protects against environmental damage. The foundation doesn't just hold up — it actively works for you while you wear it.</p>",
        "link_text": "",
        "link_type": "anchor",
        "link_anchor": "",
        "link_url": "",
        "image_asset": "lp-questions-foundation-reason-2.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
