    "bl_reason_item_evYsO5": {
      "type": "bl-reason-item",
      "name": "BL - Reason Item",
      "settings": {
        "section_id": "",
        "bg_color": "#faf9f7",
        "number": "3",
        "title": "\"Does This Foundation Match Me — Or Just Match One Version Of Me?\"",
        "body_text": "<p>You've been shade-matched at a counter. You've held bottles up to your jawline under shop lighting. You've ordered samples online and tested them in your bathroom mirror. And somehow, every shade you choose looks wrong at some point during the day, in some type of light, in some room.</p><p>That's because traditional foundations use a single, static pigment. One fixed colour mixed in a lab and poured into a bottle. But your skin doesn't have one fixed shade. Your undertone shifts with blood flow, temperature, hormones, and the light you're standing in. A static pigment can match you in one moment — but it cannot match you in every moment.</p><p>The question to ask isn't \"which shade am I?\" It's \"does this foundation adapt to my shade?\" Tone-adapting pigment technology reads your unique undertone and adjusts in real time. It looks right in fluorescent office light, in warm restaurant light, in natural daylight, and in photos. You stop thinking about your shade entirely — because it's always correct.</p>",
        "link_text": "",
        "link_type": "anchor",
        "link_anchor": "",
        "link_url": "",
        "image_asset": "lp-questions-foundation-reason-3.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
